1
00:00:32,590 --> 00:00:37,118
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Jarod was a real even-tempered man.</i>

2
00:00:37,194 --> 00:00:41,654
Stayed here for about a week,
then he was gone.

3
00:00:41,732 --> 00:00:43,825
I sort of act as
building manager here...

4
00:00:43,901 --> 00:00:47,462
but my real passion
is acupuncture.

5
00:00:47,538 --> 00:00:49,665
<i>Jarod really got into it too.</i>

6
00:00:49,740 --> 00:00:51,674
You stuck needles into him?

7
00:00:51,742 --> 00:00:55,041
<i>Actually, I taught him</i>
<i>how to do it himself.</i>

8
00:00:55,112 --> 00:00:57,273
- For what purpose?
- Stress reduction.

9
00:00:57,348 --> 00:01:01,307
I'm very good at reducing
tensions in the body.

10
00:01:01,385 --> 00:01:04,843
Funny. I'm very good
at causing them.

11
00:01:04,922 --> 00:01:09,188
Jarod wanted the needles placed
along the brachial plexus.

12
00:01:09,260 --> 00:01:13,629
<i>Brachial plexus?</i>
<i>Nerve center for the upper extremities?</i>

13
00:01:13,697 --> 00:01:16,860
<i>[Man] He wanted me to leave them in</i>
<i>until his arm was paralyzed.</i>

14
00:01:16,934 --> 00:01:18,902
<i>He'd walk around</i>
<i>like that for days.</i>

15
00:01:18,969 --> 00:01:21,062
You obviously lived
through the '60s.

16
00:01:21,138 --> 00:01:25,632
Does your companion know
the concept of free love?

17
00:01:28,245 --> 00:01:31,646
- When did he leave?
- Two days ago.

18
00:01:31,715 --> 00:01:36,379
Well, then our work here
is mercifully done.

19
00:01:36,454 --> 00:01:39,184
Oh.

20
00:01:39,256 --> 00:01:41,417
But then you'll
miss out on this.

21
00:01:44,662 --> 00:01:46,653
He said you'd know
what it meant.

22
00:02:00,411 --> 00:02:02,743
This building
isn't far from here.

23
00:02:02,813 --> 00:02:04,804
Hmm.

24
00:02:23,567 --> 00:02:27,059
[Chattering]

25
00:02:27,137 --> 00:02:29,401
- <i>[Woman] He's up there.</i>
- <i>[Sirens Wailing]</i>

26
00:02:33,143 --> 00:02:35,703
Where the hell's
my cameraman?

27
00:02:38,716 --> 00:02:41,549
- It's a long way down.
- Stay away from me.

28
00:02:41,619 --> 00:02:43,814
- Stay away from me.
- I just want to talk to you.

29
00:02:43,888 --> 00:02:45,879
Jarod, what the hell
are you doing up there?

30
00:02:45,956 --> 00:02:48,254
<i>You'd better be</i>
<i>rolling on this guy.</i>

31
00:02:49,693 --> 00:02:52,059
<i>My name's Jarod.</i>
<i>What's your name?</i>

32
00:02:53,063 --> 00:02:55,725
Dave. My name's Dave.

33
00:02:55,799 --> 00:03:00,293
<i>Beautiful family. I'm guessing that's</i>
<i>your wife and your children.</i>

34
00:03:01,405 --> 00:03:03,396
They're gone.

35
00:03:03,474 --> 00:03:06,443
They were evicted,
and now I can't find them.

36
00:03:06,510 --> 00:03:09,946
<i>Dave, I'm sure they're fine.</i>

37
00:03:10,014 --> 00:03:12,141
I'll bet they're out there
somewhere worrying about you.

38
00:03:12,216 --> 00:03:14,582
Nobody's worried about me.

39
00:03:14,652 --> 00:03:17,519
If that were true,
would I be up here on this ledge?

40
00:03:17,588 --> 00:03:20,022
<i>I'm sure that they</i>
<i>are looking for you.</i>

41
00:03:20,090 --> 00:03:22,854
<i>Why should they?</i>
<i>I drink some.</i>

42
00:03:22,927 --> 00:03:24,861
I can't hold a job.

43
00:03:24,929 --> 00:03:27,454
<i>I've lost them for good.</i>

44
00:03:27,531 --> 00:03:31,160
<i>I can help you find them, Dave.</i>
<i>Use the camera.</i>

45
00:03:31,235 --> 00:03:33,703
Tell them how much
you love them...

46
00:03:33,771 --> 00:03:37,172
how much you miss them,
how much you need them.

47
00:03:37,241 --> 00:03:40,608
<i>But first, we have to</i>
<i>get off this ledge.</i>

48
00:03:41,879 --> 00:03:44,245
Grab my hand.

49
00:03:47,184 --> 00:03:50,676
<i>[Man Narrating]</i>

50
00:04:33,797 --> 00:04:36,789
<i>[Chattering]</i>

51
00:04:39,269 --> 00:04:41,203
<i>[Jarod]</i>
<i>Grab my hand.</i>

52
00:04:41,271 --> 00:04:43,671
<i>Only thing would've made this better</i>
<i>was if thejumper was a topless dancer.</i>

53
00:04:43,741 --> 00:04:46,608
- [Laughs]
- Poor guy.

54
00:04:46,677 --> 00:04:48,941
<i>Annie, edit out some clips</i>
<i>for the promo team A.S.A.P.</i>

55
00:04:49,013 --> 00:04:52,813
This runs tonight. We gotta get some
footage of this loser's wife and kids.

56
00:04:52,883 --> 00:04:54,714
<i>Maybe they've checked into</i>
<i>a homeless shelter.</i>

57
00:04:54,785 --> 00:04:57,310
<i>After all this, don't you think the family</i>
<i>deserves a little privacy?</i>

58
00:04:57,388 --> 00:05:00,721
<i>Privacy? To get her face on the 10:00 news</i>
<i>and some party money in her pocket...</i>

59
00:05:00,791 --> 00:05:02,656
this guy's wife'll jump
at the chance.

60
00:05:02,726 --> 00:05:05,160
- No pun intended, huh?
- [Men Laugh]

61
00:05:05,229 --> 00:05:07,356
Too bad you got such
a good grip there, Jarod.

62
00:05:07,431 --> 00:05:10,889
- Why is that?
- A heroic attempt is as good as a save.

63
00:05:10,968 --> 00:05:13,801
<i>The plunge would've given</i>
<i>this piece a better punch.</i>

64
00:05:13,871 --> 00:05:15,998
Spoken like an anchorman
who wants his anchor back.

65
00:05:16,073 --> 00:05:19,008
You know, Jarod, if my instincts
are as good as I know they are...

66
00:05:19,076 --> 00:05:21,567
your face is going to be running
in every living room in America.

67
00:05:21,645 --> 00:05:23,579
Actually, I think it would play better...

68
00:05:23,647 --> 00:05:26,047
if Phil got credit for the save.

69
00:05:26,116 --> 00:05:29,347
- What?
- I mean, he's the talent.

70
00:05:29,420 --> 00:05:32,583
<i>He's the hero that everyone tunes in</i>
<i>to see each day, not me.</i>

71
00:05:32,656 --> 00:05:36,683
<i>Only problem is, our hero was standing</i>
<i>in a parking lot 100 feet below the action.</i>

72
00:05:36,760 --> 00:05:39,888
- Yes, I know, but you never saw my face.
- So?

73
00:05:39,963 --> 00:05:41,828
<i>So if you cut in just after</i>
<i>I make the grab...</i>

74
00:05:41,899 --> 00:05:44,197
we use all the coverage I shot
before I got up on the roof.

75
00:05:44,268 --> 00:05:46,896
<i>We lay in Phil's voice-over,</i>
<i>and then we tag it with...</i>

76
00:05:46,970 --> 00:05:50,371
a pickup shot of Phil exiting
the building with the jumper.

77
00:05:53,077 --> 00:05:56,444
We're not long for a two-share and last place
with that kind of attitude. Do it.

78
00:05:56,513 --> 00:05:59,038
- But Chris, it's...
- <i>Unethical?</i>

79
00:05:59,116 --> 00:06:01,243
You heard me.
Make Phil a hero.

80
00:06:03,253 --> 00:06:07,383
- I thought only God rewrote history.
- God never won sweeps.

81
00:06:11,361 --> 00:06:14,125
- <i>[Miss Parker] Beautiful part of town.</i>
- <i>[Sydney] Dangerous.</i>

82
00:06:14,198 --> 00:06:17,634
No wonderJarod left the notebook
with the acupuncturist.

83
00:06:17,701 --> 00:06:20,534
- He doesn't want us down here.
- Come on, Sydney. We're here.

84
00:06:20,604 --> 00:06:22,629
Let's see if Ratboy
left anything behind.

85
00:06:38,355 --> 00:06:41,085
This is futile.
Jarod's long gone.

86
00:06:42,092 --> 00:06:44,026
Afraid of the dark, Syd?

87
00:06:44,094 --> 00:06:46,392
Only when I
can't see what's in it.

88
00:06:46,463 --> 00:06:48,454
<i>[Clatter]</i>

89
00:06:50,501 --> 00:06:52,992
- Damn it.
- <i>[Clatter]</i>

90
00:06:54,738 --> 00:06:58,902
Miss Parker, maybe we should get
the cleanup team to check this place out.

91
00:06:58,976 --> 00:07:00,841
Forget it, Syd.

92
00:07:00,911 --> 00:07:05,575
I'd trade a dozen Ferragamos
for oneJarod any day.

93
00:07:17,795 --> 00:07:19,990
<i>[Object Clangs]</i>

94
00:07:21,298 --> 00:07:23,289
I'm counting to three.

95
00:07:23,367 --> 00:07:26,803
Then I'm going to shoot whoever you are.

96
00:07:26,870 --> 00:07:29,361
One...

97
00:07:29,439 --> 00:07:31,430
two...

98
00:07:31,508 --> 00:07:33,499
<i>Three.!</i>

99
00:07:35,279 --> 00:07:39,340
- What do you want?
- What you got?

100
00:07:39,416 --> 00:07:41,884
I have a nine millimeter
in your face...

101
00:07:41,952 --> 00:07:43,886
and you appear
to have a knife...

102
00:07:43,954 --> 00:07:46,821
a rusty knife.

103
00:07:48,292 --> 00:07:51,989
<i>Oh, you must be feeling</i>
<i>lucky today.</i>

104
00:07:52,062 --> 00:07:53,689
- <i>[Glass Shatters]</i>
- <i>[Sydney Shouts]</i>

105
00:07:54,698 --> 00:07:56,893
[Groaning]

106
00:08:00,804 --> 00:08:02,738
[Chuckles]

107
00:08:04,041 --> 00:08:08,000
Are you feeling
lucky today, hmm?

108
00:08:08,078 --> 00:08:10,376
<i>Get their wallets andjewelry</i>
<i>and let's get out ofhere.</i>

109
00:08:18,288 --> 00:08:21,280
<i>[Keyboarding]</i>

110
00:08:22,426 --> 00:08:25,054
Writing Phil's copy for him too?

111
00:08:25,128 --> 00:08:28,894
I'm just trying to send
a message to an old friend.

112
00:08:31,235 --> 00:08:33,100
<i>So you think I was wrong...</i>

113
00:08:33,170 --> 00:08:36,264
letting Phil take credit
for saving the jumper.

114
00:08:36,340 --> 00:08:38,740
As our new, esteemed news director
always reminds me...

115
00:08:38,809 --> 00:08:41,175
I get paid to cut tape,
not to think.

116
00:08:41,245 --> 00:08:44,009
From what I understand,
you win awards doing it.

117
00:08:45,349 --> 00:08:48,443
Well, awards don't count
for much around here.

118
00:08:48,518 --> 00:08:52,249
Pulitzer's rolling over in his grave,
and Nielsen's packing down the dirt.

119
00:08:52,322 --> 00:08:55,985
Phil has asked me to go over
some of his old footage...

120
00:08:56,059 --> 00:08:58,050
to see how he likes
to be shot.

121
00:08:59,663 --> 00:09:01,893
Do you think maybe you could show me
some of his old tapes?

122
00:09:01,965 --> 00:09:03,956
Yeah.

123
00:09:11,475 --> 00:09:14,137
- Second shelf.
- Great. Thank you.

124
00:09:17,748 --> 00:09:21,013
The Ken Watanabe shooting.
I heard about this.

125
00:09:21,084 --> 00:09:23,177
So has half the world.

126
00:09:23,253 --> 00:09:26,450
And our Ivy League Hitler was pissed
we didn't hook the other half.

127
00:09:26,523 --> 00:09:29,515
It's Chris's job
to know what people want...

128
00:09:29,593 --> 00:09:32,084
and it's our job to
make sure they get it.

129
00:09:32,162 --> 00:09:36,462
Which doesn't mean we should throw out
anything resembling journalistic integrity.

130
00:09:36,533 --> 00:09:38,467
If it bleeds, it leads.

131
00:09:38,535 --> 00:09:40,594
That's the new wave of the news,
Annie, like it or not.

132
00:09:40,671 --> 00:09:44,266
We either surf along with it,
or we get torn apart in the riptide.

133
00:09:46,977 --> 00:09:48,911
<i>[Annie]</i>
<i>It's really an act.</i>

134
00:09:48,979 --> 00:09:52,278
Phil actually worships Cronkite
in secret midnight rituals.

135
00:09:52,349 --> 00:09:54,374
Hmm.

136
00:09:54,451 --> 00:09:56,442
Who's Cronkite?

137
00:09:57,788 --> 00:10:00,416
You're gonna fit in just fine here.

138
00:10:04,594 --> 00:10:08,155
Tonight, exclusively
on Seattle's Channel 43...

139
00:10:08,231 --> 00:10:10,358
our continuing series
on local gangs.

140
00:10:10,434 --> 00:10:14,268
<i>In this shocking footage,</i>
<i>our own cameraman, Ken Watanabe...</i>

141
00:10:14,338 --> 00:10:16,704
<i>captured on videotape</i>
<i>a gang gathering...</i>

142
00:10:16,773 --> 00:10:19,071
at the North Puget dock area.

143
00:10:19,142 --> 00:10:22,578
But what happened next
took us both by surprise.

144
00:10:22,646 --> 00:10:24,637
Out of nowhere,
the 15th Street Bleeders...

145
00:10:24,715 --> 00:10:26,649
crashed the turf
of the Burns...

146
00:10:26,717 --> 00:10:29,083
leading to
an explosive conflict...

147
00:10:29,152 --> 00:10:31,552
a conflict in which one of
our own became a casualty.

148
00:10:31,621 --> 00:10:34,283
- Oh, God, I'm hit. Oh, God. Oh, God.
- [Gunfire]

149
00:10:34,358 --> 00:10:37,657
Phil, where are you?
Phil, I'm hit. I'm hit, man.

150
00:10:37,728 --> 00:10:40,663
<i>My arm. My arm. I can't move my arm.</i>
<i>Get me out ofhere, man.</i>

151
00:10:40,731 --> 00:10:42,528
- Get me out of here.
- Come on. Come on.

152
00:10:42,599 --> 00:10:45,864
<i>Come on. Get up.</i>

153
00:10:45,936 --> 00:10:48,803
Tonight, our prayers
are with Ken Watanabe...

154
00:10:48,872 --> 00:10:50,806
a courageous young cameraman.

155
00:10:50,874 --> 00:10:52,637
God bless you, Ken.

156
00:10:52,709 --> 00:10:57,408
<i>Phil Campbell,</i>
Channel 43 News, <i>at 10:00.</i>

157
00:11:53,470 --> 00:11:59,136
<i>Dehlila, I think about you</i>
<i>so much, my brain hurts.</i>

158
00:11:59,209 --> 00:12:02,975
I have to meet you,
to see you.

159
00:12:04,981 --> 00:12:07,449
- <i>[Phone Rings]</i>
- Samson.

160
00:12:07,517 --> 00:12:09,451
I mean, Broots.

161
00:12:10,620 --> 00:12:13,987
Mr. Parker?
Uh, Mr. Parker, sir.

162
00:12:14,057 --> 00:12:17,356
How-How can I help you, sir?

163
00:12:17,427 --> 00:12:22,387
Uh... Uh, no. No, sir, I haven't seen
your daughter since yesterday.

164
00:12:22,466 --> 00:12:24,832
Sydney neither.
I mean, either.

165
00:12:27,270 --> 00:12:30,637
Y-Yes, sir.
I'll get on it right away, sir.

166
00:12:30,707 --> 00:12:32,971
- Yeah, well, it's a pleasure talk... talk...
- [Click, Dial Tone]

167
00:12:33,043 --> 00:12:35,568
Hello? Hello?

168
00:12:46,690 --> 00:12:50,387
- <i>Jarod.!</i>
- <i>Dave?</i>

169
00:12:50,460 --> 00:12:52,485
You look great.

170
00:12:52,562 --> 00:12:55,531
A step at a time.
That's what they tell me.

171
00:12:55,599 --> 00:12:57,794
I just came by to say thanks.

172
00:12:57,868 --> 00:12:59,893
Of course,
the way that story aired...

173
00:12:59,970 --> 00:13:02,996
- I don't know if I should thank
that reporter Phil or you.
- [Laughs]

174
00:13:03,073 --> 00:13:06,975
Well, strange things happen in TV.
I'm glad you're doing well.

175
00:13:07,043 --> 00:13:09,739
I don't know what got into me.

176
00:13:09,813 --> 00:13:12,077
Did you find
your wife and kids?

177
00:13:12,149 --> 00:13:17,052
Yeah, but she doesn't want me back
until I find a job, so...

178
00:13:17,120 --> 00:13:19,816
- I'll keep my eyes open.
- Yeah.

179
00:13:19,890 --> 00:13:24,418
- What do you keep looking at?
- Oh, those wires there.

180
00:13:24,494 --> 00:13:28,692
<i>If they're planning on hooking up</i>
<i>that satellite dish to them wires...</i>

181
00:13:28,765 --> 00:13:31,427
they're gonna blow out their
electricity in nothing flat.

182
00:13:31,501 --> 00:13:35,767
- You're an electrician?
- Nope. Satcom grunt.

183
00:13:35,839 --> 00:13:39,832
I wasn't any better at jumping out of airplanes
than I am from buildings...

184
00:13:39,910 --> 00:13:43,073
but I do know a wiring problem
when I see one.

185
00:13:44,848 --> 00:13:48,682
Hey, thanks again, really.

186
00:13:48,752 --> 00:13:51,550
- Good luck.
- Thanks.

187
00:13:56,960 --> 00:14:00,589
Phil, these pieces
are excellent.

188
00:14:02,866 --> 00:14:04,993
Twenty years of broadcasting
will do that.

189
00:14:05,068 --> 00:14:07,866
I was especially impressed with
the Ken Watanabe segment.

190
00:14:07,938 --> 00:14:11,704
I was wondering. Is the raw footage
lying around somewhere?

191
00:14:11,775 --> 00:14:13,709
I'd love to see
how it was cut together.

192
00:14:13,777 --> 00:14:16,109
Most of those tapes
get recycled.

193
00:14:16,179 --> 00:14:18,147
Even with a piece this good?

194
00:14:18,215 --> 00:14:22,618
<i>Yeah, well, the station didn't use</i>
<i>to charge me for parking either.</i>

195
00:14:22,686 --> 00:14:24,677
Yeah, right.

196
00:14:36,633 --> 00:14:39,067
- Way to go, Dave.
- <i>[Chattering]</i>

197
00:14:46,076 --> 00:14:49,273
[Grunting]

198
00:14:52,649 --> 00:14:56,676
[Pipes Clanking]

199
00:14:56,753 --> 00:14:59,950
As if getting mugged
wasn't enough.

200
00:15:00,023 --> 00:15:02,093
[Weakly]
You shot me.

201
00:15:03,861 --> 00:15:06,557
I did not shoot you.

202
00:15:06,631 --> 00:15:08,622
It was an accident.

203
00:15:08,700 --> 00:15:10,793
I never liked guns.

204
00:15:10,868 --> 00:15:13,496
I hope you'll stop
carrying yours now.

205
00:15:13,571 --> 00:15:16,131
[Sighs]

206
00:15:19,777 --> 00:15:21,870
- You're bleeding again.
- [Groans]

207
00:15:21,946 --> 00:15:27,816
- I need something else to tie this wound with.
- What about that neck scarf?

208
00:15:27,885 --> 00:15:31,753
- It's one of a kind, Sydney.
- [Chuckles]

209
00:15:31,823 --> 00:15:37,420
Which is what my good leg will be
if we don't stop the bleeding.

210
00:15:47,238 --> 00:15:50,401
[Shuddering]

211
00:15:50,475 --> 00:15:52,409
I'm sorry.

212
00:15:52,477 --> 00:15:55,037
[Groaning, Grunting]

213
00:15:55,113 --> 00:15:57,104
[Sighs]

214
00:15:59,917 --> 00:16:03,853
- Thank you.
- <i>You're going into shock. You need to be warm.</i>

215
00:16:18,136 --> 00:16:20,127
Oh, my God.

216
00:16:21,139 --> 00:16:23,130
Oh, my God, Sydney.

217
00:16:23,207 --> 00:16:26,904
<i>Don't look now, but we are</i>
<i>ground zero for detonation...</i>

218
00:16:26,978 --> 00:16:29,606
to bring this dump down.

219
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:32,148
Please tell me that you told someone
where we were going.

220
00:16:35,787 --> 00:16:37,778
[Sighs]

221
00:16:41,125 --> 00:16:43,320
[Cooing]

222
00:16:46,397 --> 00:16:48,331
There's something
I don't understand.

223
00:16:49,801 --> 00:16:51,962
- What's that?
- Where are the little ones?

224
00:16:52,970 --> 00:16:54,904
<i>The what?</i>

225
00:16:54,972 --> 00:16:57,406
You always see the big pigeons,
you know, with the scars...

226
00:16:57,475 --> 00:16:59,409
<i>and the broken wings</i>
<i>and the missing legs.</i>

227
00:16:59,477 --> 00:17:02,105
<i>But you never see</i>
<i>the little ones.</i>

228
00:17:02,180 --> 00:17:05,445
- I never really thought about it.
- Hey, I know you.

229
00:17:05,516 --> 00:17:08,007
You're the cameraman
that was on the news.

230
00:17:09,220 --> 00:17:13,418
- I'm Jarod Crane.
- Ken.

231
00:17:13,491 --> 00:17:16,790
That was incredible
footage you captured.

232
00:17:16,861 --> 00:17:20,319
Thanks. I never planned on
becoming a story though.

233
00:17:20,398 --> 00:17:22,764
When are you going
back to work at the station?

234
00:17:22,834 --> 00:17:25,667
<i>And do what?</i>
<i>Log commercials?</i>

235
00:17:26,737 --> 00:17:29,433
I'm a shooter, man.

236
00:17:29,507 --> 00:17:32,738
My days on the front line
are over.

237
00:17:32,810 --> 00:17:36,644
You know, it's funny.
You plan for your life to go up one road...

238
00:17:36,714 --> 00:17:41,947
and when you finally get there,
the bridge washes out.

239
00:17:43,654 --> 00:17:45,747
Well, you never know.

240
00:17:45,823 --> 00:17:49,691
Life has a strange way
of surprising you.

241
00:17:55,433 --> 00:17:58,129
Hey, look at that.

242
00:17:58,202 --> 00:18:00,670
<i>[Ken]</i>
<i>I'll be damned.</i>

243
00:18:00,738 --> 00:18:06,074
Like I said,
life is full of surprises.

244
00:18:24,128 --> 00:18:28,326
<i>[Beeping]</i>

245
00:18:28,399 --> 00:18:33,166
Ken Watanabe and Phil Campbell,
February 18, roll number one.

246
00:18:35,172 --> 00:18:37,902
Okay. Uh...

247
00:18:37,975 --> 00:18:40,068
Nothing fancy, Kenny.
We're just gonna go in there...

248
00:18:40,144 --> 00:18:42,806
and we're gonna sit down,
and we're gonna listen to the Burns...

249
00:18:42,880 --> 00:18:44,814
talk about their side
of this turf war.

250
00:18:44,882 --> 00:18:47,112
These guys tend to talk with their guns.
Know what I'm saying?

251
00:18:47,184 --> 00:18:49,345
You don't have to worry
about getting fancy from me.

252
00:18:49,420 --> 00:18:52,048
Don't worry about it, Ken.
You'll be fine.

253
00:18:53,124 --> 00:18:56,287
[Exhales]
Let's do it.

254
00:18:58,562 --> 00:19:00,894
[Ken] You sure these guys
are gonna show?

255
00:19:00,965 --> 00:19:03,195
[Phil] Yeah, they'll be here.
Don't worry about it.

256
00:19:03,267 --> 00:19:05,792
Okay, um...

257
00:19:05,870 --> 00:19:08,464
Right up there. Head there.

258
00:19:08,539 --> 00:19:10,905
[Ken] You been hanging with
the homies, Phil, huh?

259
00:19:19,483 --> 00:19:21,451
Yo! Hey, D-Mac!

260
00:19:21,519 --> 00:19:24,420
Hey, D-Mac!
Bleeders in the hood!

261
00:19:40,137 --> 00:19:42,071
[Gunfire Resumes]

262
00:19:46,544 --> 00:19:50,139
- [Tires Screeching]
- I'm hit! I'm hit! Oh, God!

263
00:19:50,214 --> 00:19:52,842
- My arm! My arm!
- [Gunfire Continues]

264
00:19:52,917 --> 00:19:55,784
I'm hit, man! Phil,
get me out of here, man!

265
00:19:55,853 --> 00:19:59,084
- Get me out of here! Get me out of here!
- You're okay.

266
00:20:02,093 --> 00:20:04,926
Get me out of here, man!
Get me out of here! Get me out of here!

267
00:20:10,801 --> 00:20:12,962
<i>Interesting undershirt, Phil.</i>

268
00:21:04,221 --> 00:21:07,349
Flak jacket standard issue
for a street reporter now, Phil?

269
00:21:10,694 --> 00:21:12,992
I'm dying for a cigarette!

270
00:21:14,932 --> 00:21:18,231
<i>How the hell</i>
<i>did I end up here?</i>

271
00:21:18,302 --> 00:21:20,668
You regret taking on
theJarod assignment?

272
00:21:20,738 --> 00:21:24,230
- I regret a lot of things.
- Such as?

273
00:21:26,343 --> 00:21:28,868
I regret not going to the prom.

274
00:21:28,946 --> 00:21:34,907
<i>I regret laughing</i>
<i>at my first boyfriend...</i>

275
00:21:34,985 --> 00:21:37,180
when he told me I was the one.

276
00:21:38,622 --> 00:21:41,682
<i>And in this instant,</i>
<i>I regret not having...</i>

277
00:21:41,759 --> 00:21:44,956
a nicotine patch
the size of a doormat.

278
00:21:49,967 --> 00:21:51,901
[Groans]
Oh, no.

279
00:21:51,969 --> 00:21:55,598
Your ulcer, huh?
And no medication.

280
00:21:55,673 --> 00:22:01,009
[Sighs] Ladies and gentlemen,
the fabulous Sherlock Holmes.

281
00:22:04,348 --> 00:22:06,976
[Groaning]

282
00:22:10,454 --> 00:22:13,719
Let me see it, Sydney.

283
00:22:13,791 --> 00:22:18,819
Regret's often born out
of a lack of choice, you know?

284
00:22:18,896 --> 00:22:24,198
Unlike you, Syd, I don't think
that everything is out of my control.

285
00:22:29,874 --> 00:22:32,672
You do when it
comes to your father.

286
00:22:36,914 --> 00:22:40,111
Please, don't...
don't misunderstand that.

287
00:22:40,184 --> 00:22:42,345
Why don't you just say it?

288
00:22:45,322 --> 00:22:47,790
I caved.

289
00:22:47,858 --> 00:22:50,326
I always do around him.

290
00:22:52,096 --> 00:22:55,031
You can still walk up
to your father and tell him...

291
00:22:55,099 --> 00:22:58,193
<i>"Dad, I'm leaving. '"</i>

292
00:22:59,870 --> 00:23:02,532
<i>[Chuckling]</i>

293
00:23:02,606 --> 00:23:05,939
[Chuckling]

294
00:23:08,612 --> 00:23:11,604
Right. I can see it now.

295
00:23:11,682 --> 00:23:15,083
Two kids,
a little yellow house...

296
00:23:15,152 --> 00:23:17,848
chitchatting with the girls
over lattes at the mall.

297
00:23:19,056 --> 00:23:21,786
You still have a future,
Miss Parker.

298
00:23:21,859 --> 00:23:25,226
It's a hell of a future,
sitting here waiting to get blown to bits.

299
00:23:27,164 --> 00:23:28,859
[Chuckles]

300
00:23:28,933 --> 00:23:31,401
[Laughing]

301
00:23:33,571 --> 00:23:38,235
Here I am, trying to comfort you.
[Laughing Continues]

302
00:23:40,744 --> 00:23:45,044
As if anything you could ever do
would give me comfort.

303
00:23:52,356 --> 00:23:54,517
It did once.

304
00:23:59,263 --> 00:24:01,197
You are one hell
of a thrower, Jarod.

305
00:24:01,265 --> 00:24:04,860
It's about understanding
the projectile's aerodynamics.

306
00:24:04,935 --> 00:24:09,804
Well, actually,
I just close one eye and let it fly.

307
00:24:09,873 --> 00:24:12,671
- Oh.
- That's it. Good game.

308
00:24:12,743 --> 00:24:15,177
I should've warned you.
I don't like to lose.

309
00:24:15,246 --> 00:24:18,409
- Good man.
- Next round's on me.

310
00:24:18,482 --> 00:24:20,211
[Patrons Cheering]

311
00:24:20,284 --> 00:24:23,845
Phil certainly is
in a good mood tonight.

312
00:24:23,921 --> 00:24:28,187
You must be very proud of Annie and Phil getting
nominated for the Ken Watanabe segment.

313
00:24:28,259 --> 00:24:31,524
Yeah, even stiffs like Phil get lucky.
If only Grecian Formula were talent.

314
00:24:31,595 --> 00:24:35,395
<i>Awards help the promo guys, I suppose.</i>
<i>They also make a news team lazy.</i>

315
00:24:35,466 --> 00:24:38,594
News is about being hungry.
Always has been.

316
00:24:38,669 --> 00:24:42,264
You guys gonna drink water all night,
or are you coming to join the real party?

317
00:24:44,975 --> 00:24:48,069
And you, smile.

318
00:24:48,145 --> 00:24:51,410
<i>[Laughing]</i>

319
00:24:52,516 --> 00:24:55,952
- Is this about Ken?
- He should be here.

320
00:24:56,020 --> 00:24:58,648
Somebody forgot to invite him.

321
00:24:58,722 --> 00:25:00,246
[Inaudible]

322
00:25:00,324 --> 00:25:03,816
<i>He must've been very proud,</i>
<i>taking one for the team.</i>

323
00:25:03,894 --> 00:25:08,922
<i>[Chris] KTJE's got a hell of a medical package.</i>
<i>Watanabe's all right.</i>

324
00:25:08,999 --> 00:25:11,934
<i>Ken's gonna be fine.</i>
<i>Look, everybody in this business knows...</i>

325
00:25:12,002 --> 00:25:14,630
that putting your tail on
the line is a job requirement.

326
00:25:14,705 --> 00:25:20,075
<i>Ken was green.</i>
<i>He was too zealous, and it cost him.</i>

327
00:25:20,144 --> 00:25:23,910
If I'd have known how dangerous it was,
I never would've let him go out there.

328
00:25:23,981 --> 00:25:26,449
I'm sure you wouldn't.

329
00:25:37,161 --> 00:25:41,461
I'm not trying to be a pest, but I've got the
Tower breathing down my neck to find them.

330
00:25:41,532 --> 00:25:46,697
Now surely there's got to be a Sweeper team
somewhere near the New York City area.

331
00:25:46,770 --> 00:25:50,831
Excuse me? What business is it of yours
what my clearance level is?

332
00:25:50,908 --> 00:25:53,843
- Now, listen. You S.I.S. guys
are really startin' to tick me off.
- <i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

333
00:25:53,911 --> 00:25:55,902
Hold on a second.
Just hold on.

334
00:25:55,979 --> 00:25:58,709
- Broots!
- It's me.

335
00:25:58,782 --> 00:26:00,943
Don't bother trying to trace me.

336
00:26:01,018 --> 00:26:04,146
- I've scrambled the source signal.
- Jarod?

337
00:26:06,724 --> 00:26:10,524
- I've been trying to contact Sydney.
- Join the party.

338
00:26:10,594 --> 00:26:14,462
He and Miss Parker went looking for you two
days ago. We haven't heard from them since.

339
00:26:14,531 --> 00:26:18,968
She's too persistent for her own good.
You're going to have to find them.

340
00:26:19,036 --> 00:26:21,163
You don't know how peaceful
it's been here without her.

341
00:26:21,238 --> 00:26:23,172
Would it be more peaceful
working for Raines?

342
00:26:23,240 --> 00:26:27,973
- Mr. Raines? No.
- Take down this address.

343
00:26:28,045 --> 00:26:32,175
1811 North Bushnell Street,
the Bronx.

344
00:26:43,994 --> 00:26:47,225
[Crying]

345
00:26:47,297 --> 00:26:50,289
[Soft Chattering]

346
00:27:09,820 --> 00:27:11,811
Miss Parker?

347
00:27:45,789 --> 00:27:48,553
Tell me again
how my mother died.

348
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:58,134
Stop torturing yourself.

349
00:27:58,202 --> 00:28:00,796
I know it wasn't suicide.

350
00:28:03,040 --> 00:28:05,804
Was she murdered because
of the rescued children?

351
00:28:08,545 --> 00:28:12,174
- I don't know.
- Was it my father?

352
00:28:14,284 --> 00:28:20,245
Miss Parker, I know about your mother's life,
not about her death.

353
00:28:20,324 --> 00:28:22,292
<i>She was a kind woman...</i>

354
00:28:22,359 --> 00:28:27,888
a driving force at the Centre in those days
when it was still involved in...

355
00:28:29,766 --> 00:28:31,757
altruistic projects.

356
00:28:34,104 --> 00:28:38,871
I can't believe the Centre
was ever involved with anything positive.

357
00:28:38,942 --> 00:28:44,778
We helped four countries become
democracies during the cold war.

358
00:28:44,848 --> 00:28:50,286
<i>We brought the sides together</i>
<i>for the Korean Peace Accord.</i>

359
00:28:50,354 --> 00:28:55,189
And rumor has it that we even
helped design the Popemobile.

360
00:28:56,927 --> 00:29:00,863
<i>The Centre</i>
<i>saved thousands oflives</i>...

361
00:29:00,931 --> 00:29:06,597
lives that
they later reclaimed...

362
00:29:06,670 --> 00:29:10,606
as it turned out,
in other ways.

363
00:29:10,674 --> 00:29:14,542
Why didn't you leave
when things turned?

364
00:29:15,679 --> 00:29:18,671
<i>There were others</i>
<i>whose welfare...</i>

365
00:29:18,749 --> 00:29:23,880
was of more concern to me
than my own.

366
00:29:23,954 --> 00:29:25,717
Jarod.

367
00:29:25,789 --> 00:29:29,247
He's not very different from us,
you know?

368
00:29:29,326 --> 00:29:35,287
<i>We'd all have taken</i>
<i>very different paths...</i>

369
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:38,732
had we had our way.

370
00:29:45,309 --> 00:29:48,005
- Here you go. Pass the ball, man.
- [Chattering]

371
00:29:50,581 --> 00:29:54,244
- Boo-ya!
- Excuse me. Excuse me.

372
00:29:55,519 --> 00:29:58,420
I think that was traveling.

373
00:29:58,488 --> 00:30:02,584
You must be crazy,
stupid or both.

374
00:30:02,659 --> 00:30:07,028
No, no. After you lifted your pivot foot,
you took more than the allotted two steps...

375
00:30:07,097 --> 00:30:09,031
as outlined in
the official rule book.

376
00:30:09,099 --> 00:30:13,729
- Mmm.
- Pizza?

377
00:30:13,804 --> 00:30:16,364
Thank you, anyway,
but it already comes presliced.

378
00:30:17,608 --> 00:30:19,701
Help yourselves.

379
00:30:19,776 --> 00:30:22,939
- What, you got a death wish or something, man?
- Not that I know of.

380
00:30:23,013 --> 00:30:25,208
Didn't your mama ever tell you
that white people shouldn't...

381
00:30:25,282 --> 00:30:27,216
go walking through
other people's neighborhoods?

382
00:30:27,284 --> 00:30:31,311
Well, I never actually knew my mother,
so I guess the answer is no.

383
00:30:31,388 --> 00:30:35,085
My name's Jarod Crane.
I'm with <i>Channel 43 News.</i>

384
00:30:35,158 --> 00:30:37,626
I'm looking for a D-Mac.

385
00:30:40,397 --> 00:30:43,264
- You gonna put him on TV?
- Quite possibly, yes.

386
00:30:44,901 --> 00:30:48,928
- I'm D-Mac.
- Nice to meet you.

387
00:30:52,414 --> 00:30:54,678
<i>Ow.! He's got game.</i>
<i>The boy's got some game.</i>

388
00:30:54,750 --> 00:30:57,480
[Chattering]

389
00:30:59,021 --> 00:31:01,649
Hey, man, that camera guy
shouldn't have been there.

390
00:31:01,724 --> 00:31:04,625
- Tell me what happened.
- <i>A man hits my cell phone.</i>

391
00:31:04,693 --> 00:31:08,686
He must've paid somebody
off to get the number. Sounded white.

392
00:31:08,764 --> 00:31:12,495
Tells me he wants to talk about
the turf wars. Sounded cool to me.

393
00:31:12,568 --> 00:31:16,561
This white man that called you,
is that unusual?

394
00:31:19,241 --> 00:31:21,232
You really didn't have
no mother, did you?

395
00:31:25,581 --> 00:31:27,515
I never knew my old lady either.

396
00:31:29,151 --> 00:31:32,177
<i>Later I heard word the Bleeders</i>
<i>got the same call.</i>

397
00:31:32,254 --> 00:31:36,657
<i>They show up, and boom, boom,</i>
<i>the fireworks started.</i>

398
00:31:37,860 --> 00:31:39,851
Do you remember what day
you got this call?

399
00:31:39,928 --> 00:31:43,557
I don't know.
Hey, Duane, man, bring my Day Runner.

400
00:31:46,468 --> 00:31:50,768
We're bangers, not cavemen.
Thanks, man.

401
00:31:50,839 --> 00:31:55,538
Okay, here you go.
February 18, at about 8:00 at night.

402
00:31:59,414 --> 00:32:01,348
Could you tell me
your cell phone number?

403
00:32:08,023 --> 00:32:10,719
<i>[Chattering]</i>

404
00:32:47,863 --> 00:32:50,661
[Crying]

405
00:32:56,071 --> 00:32:58,699
- Take Miss Parker upstairs.
- Yes, sir.

406
00:33:00,475 --> 00:33:03,501
You get some rest now.

407
00:33:03,579 --> 00:33:08,107
- If you ever want to talk to me, I'm always here.
- [Crying Continues]

408
00:33:08,183 --> 00:33:11,778
- Okay?
- Thank you, Sydney.

409
00:33:33,108 --> 00:33:35,099
Sydney?

410
00:33:36,478 --> 00:33:42,041
Why is everyone wearing black?
How come you're so sad?

411
00:33:42,117 --> 00:33:47,077
We're remembering someone
who has left us, Jarod.

412
00:33:47,155 --> 00:33:49,953
Is it the woman that got shot
in the elevator?

413
00:33:50,025 --> 00:33:52,016
Miss Parker's mother, isn't it?

414
00:33:52,094 --> 00:33:56,656
Don't you ever speak of that
to anyone ever again, understand?

415
00:34:02,671 --> 00:34:04,662
[Groans]

416
00:34:19,588 --> 00:34:21,556
I could've saved him.

417
00:34:21,623 --> 00:34:23,614
Who?

418
00:34:25,093 --> 00:34:27,186
Jarod.

419
00:34:27,262 --> 00:34:30,993
He should have lived
a normal life.

420
00:34:31,066 --> 00:34:33,899
- They would've killed you.
- [Chuckles]

421
00:34:33,969 --> 00:34:39,532
You can't kill someone
who's already dead.

422
00:34:39,608 --> 00:34:41,667
<i>[Shuddering]</i>

423
00:34:55,757 --> 00:34:58,624
You do remember.

424
00:35:08,103 --> 00:35:10,936
You broke into my edit file
and stole footage?

425
00:35:11,006 --> 00:35:13,201
"Borrowed" is more like it.

426
00:35:13,275 --> 00:35:16,073
- And I did it for Ken Watanabe.
- You lost me.

427
00:35:16,144 --> 00:35:18,840
- Ken was set up.
- What are you talking about?

428
00:35:18,914 --> 00:35:22,748
What happened to Ken happened
because Phil is desperate for ratings.

429
00:35:22,818 --> 00:35:24,911
l-l-I don't buy that.

430
00:35:24,987 --> 00:35:27,922
Buy it.

431
00:35:27,990 --> 00:35:33,724
Why else would Phil have been wearing a
bulletproof vest the night that Ken was shot?

432
00:35:40,202 --> 00:35:42,329
You actually think Phil would do
something like that?

433
00:35:42,404 --> 00:35:45,601
I'm certain of it.
Annie, you know him.

434
00:35:45,674 --> 00:35:48,973
You've seen the kind of pressure
that Phil has been under to get back on top.

435
00:35:49,044 --> 00:35:51,308
Yeah, but to risk
somebody else's life.

436
00:35:51,380 --> 00:35:53,314
He's a desperate man, Annie.

437
00:35:53,382 --> 00:35:55,850
He was the king of the hill,
and now he's on his way out.

438
00:35:55,917 --> 00:36:01,253
Annie, I need your help
to stop him.

439
00:36:08,930 --> 00:36:12,058
<i>Hello, Dave. This is Jarod.</i>

440
00:36:12,134 --> 00:36:14,898
How would you like to
come to work for Channel 43?

441
00:36:14,970 --> 00:36:19,304
Uh-huh. You can tell your wife
you've got a job.

442
00:36:19,374 --> 00:36:21,740
<i>[Rap, Indistinct]</i>

443
00:36:25,647 --> 00:36:27,376
Lights.

444
00:36:28,417 --> 00:36:31,853
<i>[Continues]</i>

445
00:36:31,920 --> 00:36:34,218
Camera.

446
00:36:40,662 --> 00:36:45,497
Hello, Annie. I'm setting up
a very special screening in Chris's office.

447
00:36:45,567 --> 00:36:50,027
I want you to do me a favor.
Make sure the general manager is there.

448
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:54,006
Action.

449
00:36:55,310 --> 00:36:57,301
<i>[Jarod]</i>
<i>Phil.</i>

450
00:36:58,914 --> 00:37:02,406
Chris just got word of a summit going down
between two rival gangs.

451
00:37:02,484 --> 00:37:06,284
He thinks it's going to make a terrific
follow-up to the Ken Watanabe segment.

